To break this down into four different development plans, we can focus on key areas that align with the competencies and skills needed for the Lead Data Scientist role. Here’s how we can divide the development plan:

1. Project Leadership Development Plan

Development Goal:

	•	Improve leadership skills by taking ownership of full data science projects, from initiation to delivery.

Success Measures:

	•	Lead at least two significant data science projects independently, showcasing decision-making and strategic planning.
	•	Receive positive feedback on project leadership from stakeholders and team members.

Skill Development:

	•	Project management and leadership in data science projects.
	•	Decision-making with minimal oversight.

Competency Development:

	•	Strategic thinking for project alignment with business objectives.
	•	Communication of project progress and outcomes to stakeholders.

Development Timeframe:

	•	Over the next 6-12 months.

Action Plan:

	•	Take the lead on upcoming data science projects.
	•	Propose and scope new projects that address business problems.
	•	Receive mentorship from current project leaders.
	•	Regularly report project updates to stakeholders and management.

2. Business Acumen & Strategic Alignment Development Plan

Development Goal:

	•	Enhance understanding of business goals and align data science efforts to support strategic objectives.

Success Measures:

	•	Contribute to strategic decision-making through data-driven insights.
	•	Participate in business meetings and provide input on how data science can solve business challenges.

Skill Development:

	•	Business acumen related to insurance and finance.
	•	Strategic alignment of data science with business goals.

Competency Development:

	•	Business communication and ability to translate technical outcomes into business value.
	•	Understanding of key business performance metrics and how they relate to data science.

Development Timeframe:

	•	Over the next 6-12 months.

Action Plan:

	•	Attend key business meetings to better understand company objectives.
	•	Work closely with business stakeholders to define data science projects that align with business priorities.
	•	Take training in business strategy or insurance-related topics.

3. Mentorship & Team Leadership Development Plan

Development Goal:

	•	Develop mentorship and team leadership skills by guiding junior team members and contributing to team collaboration.

Success Measures:

	•	Act as a mentor for junior data scientists and provide guidance on technical and project work.
	•	Receive feedback from mentees and management on leadership effectiveness.

Skill Development:

	•	Mentoring junior team members in both technical skills and career development.
	•	Team leadership in collaborative projects.

Competency Development:

	•	Coaching and providing constructive feedback.
	•	Developing leadership skills in a non-managerial role.

Development Timeframe:

	•	Over the next 6 months.

Action Plan:

	•	Take responsibility for mentoring at least one junior team member.
	•	Offer guidance during team meetings and share best practices.
	•	Participate in internal leadership training focused on coaching and mentorship.

4. Communication & Stakeholder Management Development Plan

Development Goal:

	•	Strengthen communication skills, especially in translating complex technical work into clear, actionable insights for non-technical stakeholders.

Success Measures:

	•	Effectively communicate project outcomes and technical concepts to business stakeholders, resulting in actionable decisions.
	•	Receive positive feedback from stakeholders on the clarity of communication.

Skill Development:

	•	Business communication and stakeholder management.
	•	Simplifying complex technical findings for broader audiences.

Competency Development:

	•	Influence and negotiation in cross-functional teams.
	•	Ability to present data science work in business terms.

Development Timeframe:

	•	Over the next 6 months.

Action Plan:

	•	Present key findings to stakeholders and leadership in regular project updates.
	•	Take part in communication training focused on delivering technical concepts to non-technical audiences.
	•	Seek feedback on communication style and effectiveness after meetings or presentations.

Summary of Timeframes:

	•	Project Leadership: 6-12 months.
	•	Business Acumen: 6-12 months.
	•	Mentorship: 6 months.
	•	Communication: 6 months.

These four plans break down the essential skills and competencies you need to develop, each with its own goal, measures, and action steps. Let me know if you need further adjustments or clarifications!

5. Cross-Team Collaboration & External Engagement Development Plan

Development Goal:

	•	Build collaboration with other teams and managers to identify shared opportunities, and participate in technical or business-oriented events to enhance knowledge sharing and technical communication.

Success Measures:

	•	Successfully initiate at least two collaborative projects or shared initiatives with other teams.
	•	Actively participate in relevant conferences or technical-business events, and share the insights or outcomes with the team.
	•	Provide clear and actionable communication of results to other teams or stakeholders when requested.

Skill Development:

	•	Cross-functional collaboration and identification of shared opportunities for team and project synergies.
	•	Technical communication and engagement with external or industry stakeholders.

Competency Development:

	•	Networking and building relationships across teams and departments.
	•	Representing your team in external conferences or technical events to identify industry trends and best practices.

Development Timeframe:

	•	Over the next 6-12 months.

Action Plan:

	•	Identify and initiate collaborative projects with other teams (e.g., engineering, business analytics, or operations).
	•	Attend at least two technical or business-oriented conferences or industry events in the next 12 months.
	•	Share the outcomes of external events and how they can benefit internal projects with the broader team.
	•	Communicate results and insights with other teams or stakeholders when asked, ensuring that information is shared efficiently.
	•	Establish regular touchpoints with other teams to discuss potential shared benefits or collaboration opportunities.
